    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup for **Ghost Ride the WHIP** is anchored by a high-upside outfield and corner infield trio that capitalizes on favorable park factors and platoon splits. **Mickey Moniak** leads the way with an elite 75.75 score, benefiting from a massive +14% park boost and strong platoon alignment against Burrows. Similarly, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (73.11) and **James Wood** (73.10) provide the top-end production we prioritize; **James Wood** is particularly well-positioned, as his leadoff spot contributes a +10% boost to his efficiency, while **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** continues to be a focal point of our offensive strategy. We are also leaning heavily into **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.59) and **Corbin Carroll** (68.01), with **Corbin Carroll** specifically flagged for a +4% boost due to a slow opposing delivery that increases his stolen base potential\u2014the most critical variable in our 5x5 build.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today was keeping **Zach McKinstry** on the bench; his score of 50.73 makes him a high-end utility option, but he ultimately lost out to the superior platoon efficiency and lineup positioning of our middle infielders. While **Trevor Story** and **Jose Caballero** occupy those spots, we are mindful of the risks attached to **Jose Caballero**, whose score is suppressed by a bottom-of-the-order penalty and negative platoon splits against Civale. On the injury/depth front, we continue to monitor the status of **Seiya Suzuki**, **Brice Turang**, **Dalton Rushing**, **Carson Williams**, **Gabriel Arias**, and **Travis Bazzana** as we balance our game cap constraints. We also advise caution with **Gabriel Moreno** and **Josh Naylor**, who face elite arms in Peralta and Eovaldi, respectively; while they are in the lineup, their sub-51 scores serve as a reminder that we are riding the floor today rather than expecting a ceiling performance from the C and 1B slots.",
